{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512637"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11933"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11933"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.02,0.05,0.04,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4529"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44125"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4529"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29097"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6985"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44125"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman attends the Emergency Department with a five-hour history of a severe headache. The headache started suddenly in the back of her head and reached maximum intensity within seconds. It was associated with nausea and vomiting. Two hours after the headache started, she experienced neck pain and felt uncomfortable with the light. She has no history of similar attacks of headache. She has a medical history of multiple renal cysts identified on a CT scan several years ago. She takes no regular medications. On examination her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 160/90 mmHg, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is limitation and pain on neck flexion. Fundus examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial meningitis","Cluster headache","Hypertensive encephalopathy","Migraine","Subarachnoid haemorrhage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA sudden onset of exploding headache (often described as the \u201cworst headache of life\u201d), that peaks within a minute (thunderclap headache), should be investigated for \u003Cstrong\u003Esubarachnoid haemorrhage \u003C/strong\u003E(SAH). The patient also presented with other features of SAH including pain and stiffness in the neck, photophobia, and vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUp to 95% of patients with \u003Cstrong\u003Ebacterial meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E have at least two of the four following symptoms: fever (usually high grade), headache, stiff neck, or altered mental status. Other symptoms can include nausea, vomiting, photophobia, sleepiness, confusion, irritability, delirium, and coma. In this case, the onset and severity of headache suggest SAH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headache \u003C/strong\u003Epresents with attacks of excruciating pain, which last between 15 minutes and three hours, occurring from once every other day to up to eight per day. The patient is extremely restless and agitated and often sweats profusely, with tearing and nasal congestion. The striking feature is the circadian rhythmicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the acute or subacute onset of lethargy, confusion, headache, visual disturbance (including blindness), and seizures. It is usually associated with retinal hemorrhages, exudates, or papilloedema. Rarely, hypertensive encephalopathy presents with a thunderclap headache simulating subarachnoid haemorrhage or with focal neurologic deficits simulating acute ischaemic stroke. It usually occurs above a mean arterial pressure (MAP) of about 160 mmHg (lower for normotensive people whose BP suddenly increases).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine\u003C/strong\u003E presents as recurrent throbbing or pulsating, moderate to severe, and often unilateral pain that lasts 4\u201372 hours with complete freedom between the attacks. The headache is associated with nausea, vomiting and/or sensitivity to light, sound, or smell. In this case, a patient presentation with an abrupt onset of severe headache reaching maximum intensity in less than one minute together with meningism in absence of previous headache attacks would make migraine unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH) should be considered in any patient with a clear history of abrupt onset of severe headache."],"references":["Ogunlaja OI, Cowan R. Subarachnoid hemorrhage and headache. Curr Pain Headache Rep. 2019;23(6):44. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31123920/","Brouwer MC, Van De Beek D. Bacterial Meningitis. Manson\u0027s Tropical Diseases, Fourth Edition. Elsevier; 405-414.","Nesbitt AD, Goadsby PJ. Cluster headache. BMJ. 2012;344(apr11 1):e2407. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22496300/","Williams O, Brust JCM. Hypertensive encephalopathy. Curr Treat Options Cardiovasc Med. 2004;6(3):209\u201316. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15096312/","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012;6(3):124\u201332. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26516483/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29097"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11933"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29097"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-07T12:42:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-07T12:42:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4529"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44125"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{